       The  groff  mm  macros  are  intended  to be compatible with the DWB mm
       macros with the following limitations:

       ••      No Bell Labs localisms are implemented.

       ••      The macros OK and PM are not implemented.

       ••      groff mm does not support cut marks.

       mmmm is intended to support easy localization.  Use mmmmssee  as  an  example
       how  to  adapt  the  output  format  to a national standard.  Localized
       strings  are   collected   in   the   file   _d_:_/_u_s_r_/_s_h_a_r_e_/_g_r_o_f_f_/_1_._2_2_._4_/
       _t_m_a_c_/xx_._t_m_a_c, where _x_x denotes the two-letter code for the _l_a_n_g_u_a_g_e, as
       defined in the ISO 639 standard.  For Swedish, this is ‘sv.tmac’ –  not
       ‘se’,  which  is  the ISO 3166 two-letter code for the _c_o_u_n_t_r_y (as used
       for the output format localization).

       A file called _l_o_c_a_l_e or country___l_o_c_a_l_e is read after the initialization
       of  the  global  variables.   It  is therefore possible to localize the
       macros with a different company name and so on.

       In this manual, square brackets are used to show optional arguments.

